        "author_association": "MEMBER",
        "body": "If I were to do this I would probably add this information in the Array and Dataframe constructors\r\n\r\n```python\r\nclass Array:\r\n    def __init__(self, name, chunks, dtype, graph, ...):\r\n        ...\r\n        graph.layers[name].type = Array\r\n        graph.layers[name].chunks = chunks\r\n        graph.layers[name].dtype = dtype\r\n```\r\n\r\n(pseudocode, probably breaks many things) (also, same for dataframe)\r\n\r\nI might do this, see if it passes tests, and then move on.\r\n\r\nNext, I would probably start looking at what a high level visualization might be, and how we might build that visualization.  We currently have two different technologies for visualizing this information\r\n\r\n1.  Basic HTML table views for nbytes, dtypes, etc..\r\n2.  Our home-grown svg visualization code for chunk structure\r\n3. `dot`/graphviz for high level graph layout\r\n\r\nI don't know if it's easy to combine `dot` with custom svg images and tables, but if so, that would be grand.  If not then we might want to think about our own SVG layout for these graphs.  This would probably require some blackboard or pen-and-paper thinking.  \r\n\r\n\r\nAfter this looks decent enough to be valuable then we might have enough motivation to include mangling the graph layers with collection metadata.  There would probably be an interesting conversation.\r\n\r\nAfter that I would probably try to nerd-snipe others to use this same information for high level graph optimizations.  One possible ~sucker~ volunteer is @rjzamora, who has been thinking about pushing down column selection through the graph.",
